            .page-header
              h1.h2.
                What is #[em useragent.codes] ?
            p.
              A small and easy but useful webservice to identify user-agents (browsers).
              I created it because I needed to identify browser + OS on another project.
              Browscap was not possible to use, because it gives you a 73MB JSON (minified).
              Not a good choice for a JavaScript-only frontend project.

          section
            .page-header
              h1.h2 Why do I need it?
            p.
              Have you (as a developer) ever tried to identify you browser & OS via #[code navigator.useragent] by yourself?
              <br>
              You have to parse this string and often it looks very different on various browsers and systems.
            p.
              Believe me, you don't want to do this by yourself. #[strong It sucks].

          section
            .page-header
              h1.h2 How does it work?
            p.
              #[strong It's simple:]
              <br>
              I used #[a(href="https://github.com/ua-parser/uap-php" target="_blank") UA-Parser's PHP implementation] and put it on a server.
              It returns a JSON string with all the available information.

          section
            .page-header
              h1.h2 How do I use it?
            p.
              Just request #[a(href="https://useragent.codes/get") https://useragent.codes/get] and the response will look something like this:
              <br>

